**The Viṣṇu Smṛti enumerates the proper times for ritual bathing (alongside fire oblations) as occurring at the two twilights (morning and evening) for a Vedic student (*brahmacārin*), as part of his obligatory daily worship (*sandhyā*).*[^1]*

**Full context:**  
// Vi_28.2 // Worship at the two twilights.[^2]  
// Vi_28.3 // He shall mutter his prayers standing at the morning twilight, and seated at the evening twilight.[^3]  
// Vi_28.4 // The performance of bathing and the fire-oblation at both times.[^4]  
// Vi_28.5 // Submersion in water like a staff.[^5]

No other passage in the Viṣṇu Smṛti explicitly enumerates "proper times" for ritual bathing in this way (e.g., no list of dawn/noon/dusk for householders). Bathing is prescribed at the "three junctures of the day" (*triḥsandaḥ*, i.e., morning, noon, evening) only in specific penance contexts.[^6]

