**In the Nāradasmṛti (also known as Naradasmriti), the 18 titles of law—known as *vyavahāra-padas* or topics of litigation—are enumerated in the opening *Mātṛkā* (table of contents) section of Chapter 1.**[^1]

These are introduced as follows: "It has eight limbs, eighteen topics, and likewise a hundred branches."[^2] The 18 topics (*vyavahāra-padas*) are then listed across four verses (Nar. M1.16–19):

1. Non-payment of debt (*ṛṇa-pratidenā*);  
2. Deposits (*nikṣepa*);  
3. Partnership (*saṁsṛṣṭi* or *samaya*);  
4. Resumption of a gift (*dattāpratikṣepa*);  
5. Refusal to render service after agreeing to it (*vetana-pratidenā* or *pratibhū-pratidenā*);  
6. Non-payment of wages (*karpaṇa* or *vetana*);  
7. Sale by one who is not the owner (*asvāmiki-krayā*);  
8. Non-delivery of a sold article (*krayavatāpradāna*);  
9. Rescission of a purchase (*krayavikrayā*);  
10. Breach of an agreement (*samayacchedā*);  
11. Disputes concerning land (*bhūmika*);  
12. The relationship between man and woman (*strī-puṁsamayā*);  
13. Inheritance (*dāyabhāga*);  
14. Crimes of violence (*sāhasa*);  
15. Verbal assault (*vākpāruṣya*);  
16. Physical assault (*daṇḍapāruṣya*);  
17. Gambling and betting (*dyūta*);  
18. Miscellaneous matters (*prakīrṇaka*).[^3][^4][^5][^6]

The text states that these 18 are further subdivided into 100 branches (or 108 according to some counts).[^7] Each of the 18 titles is then elaborated in dedicated sections later in the chapter (e.g., "1. Non-payment of Debt," up to "18. Miscellaneous Matters"), providing rules, procedures, and punishments specific to that topic.[^8]

